Scholastic has too many divisions.  I understand that is how you need to keep things organized on your end, but on ours, it causes confusion to the point some will choose to use a different vendor.  I am the Purchasing Coordinator and tried to make it easy by talking with my reps and labeling each vendor by, club, fair, magazine, teacher resource and yet....this time, there was another entitiy that did not fit the criteria of the four I already had in the system. I am a retired guy with excess personal means who is currently sponsoring teachers' classroom wish lists at two elementary schools. These are items which are outside of their allotted budgets. You are the ONLY site I've ever encountered which has stone-walled my attempts to buy classroom materials. Do you need the two schools in question to vouch for my donor history in order to allow me to direct purchase from the site that teachers and parents use? Being referred to your store.scholastic.com site is a worthless exercise since the titles requested by teachers have so far not generally been available on that site. I understand the discounts offered by the book publishers may have created contractual obligations for selling to schools or parents only. But surely, if I can be vouched for by Lowell Elementary School (Duluth, MN) and Northern Lights Elementary School (Superior, WI) - you ought to be able to allow me to create an account which I expect will generate in total a four figure sum in book orders over the indefinite span of time I intend to do this gifting. Can we figure out a way to make it easier for you to sell more books and still remain within the framework of whatever contracts you're obliged to honor ?  Thanks for any help - Geof Witrak, Duluth, MN  (218-428-7025)

With the first person to respond to my question/request I felt she just wanted to give me a hard time. Five stars to the second person to respond to my question. It was more direct to the point that you can do something on your end. This kind of service is what us grandparents need. Thank you.

BTW, i try to order from each of my grandkids so their teachers can get points.   But the flimsy quality of the books is becoming a deterrent.  I spend more $ on tape to get more than one reading out of them. Good luck to you all, sanchezmln56@gmail.com

Initially, I contacted customer service by phone to check in on an order for the new Dog Man book. The individual I spoke with informed me that the cut off date to order the book and receive it on the release date was March 20th. Then she noted that my student had placed the order online on March 20th, but that the book order was not processed until the release date of March 28th. That didn't really make sense to me if he ordered within the deadline, but she couldn't provide any other answers. So I used the Live Chat online and they told me that the cut off date for ordering was actually March 19th. So my student had missed the cut off date, which would explain way he hadn't received the book yet. Not a big deal, we were happy to figure out why the book hadn't arrived yet.

(A couple of books were damaged also.) Thank goodness the delivery date is Wednesday, so if it comes late in the day, (students go home at 2 on Wednesday), I will be able to distribute them on Thursday.
